{{Infobox website | name = Tea Party Community | logo = Tea Party Community Logo.png | caption = First logo when the site launched (now outdated). | screenshot = Tea Party Community Screen Shot.jpg | screenshot_size = 240px | collapsible = Yes | url = {{URL|https://teapartycommunity.com/ |teapartycommunity.com}} | type = [[Social networking service]] | registration = Required | language = | num_users = 153,902 | owner = | author = {{plainlist | * Tim Selaty Sr., Founder – CEO * Tim Selaty Jr., Founder – CTO * Michelle Selaty, Founder – CFO }}<ref name=About>{{cite web | url=https://www.teapartycommunity.com/about/ | title=About | publisher=Tea Party Community | accessdate=February 1, 2013}}</ref> | launch_date = {{Start date|2013|02|02}} | alexa = | revenue = |publisher= | current_status = Active }}
The '''Tea Party Community''' is a [[social networking website|social networking]] and political networking<ref name=ti/> website intended as an alternative to [[Facebook]] for use by [[conservatism in the United States|American conservatives]], founded by Ken Crow, Tim Selaty, Sr. and Tim Selaty, Jr. in November 2012<ref name=fn/> and launching on February 2, 2013.<ref name=ti>{{cite web|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/505463/tea-party-community-facebook-alternative-for-conservatives-launching/|title='Tea Party Community': 'Facebook' Alternative For Conservatives Launching|date=February 1, 2013|accessdate=February 2, 2013|work=The Inquisitr|first=Tara|last=Dodrill}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theblaze.com/stories/2013/01/31/conservatives-launch-new-social-network-to-escape-facebook-censorship/|title=Conservatives Launch New Social Network to Escape Facebook 'Censorship' — Will You Join?|date=January 31, 2013|accessdate=February 2, 2013|work=[[TheBlaze]]|first=Jason|last=Howerton}}</ref> In January 2013, Crow accused Facebook of intentionally targeting conservative members for censorship and described the new site as "a new home for conservatives and the [[Tea Party movement]] in America", which could help to facilitate "the organizational process" of the movement. The Tea Party Community is aesthetically similar to Facebook, which Crow described as intentional.<ref name=fn>{{cite web|url=http://radio.foxnews.com/toddstarnes/top-stories/conservatives-launch-facebook-alternative.html|title=Conservatives Launch Facebook Alternative|date=January 31, 2013|accessdate=February 2, 2013|work=[[Fox News Radio]]|first=Todd|last=Starnes}}</ref> As of February 1, 2013, it had drawn over 50,000 members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/02/01/tea-party-community_n_2598171.html|title=Tea Party Community, Conservative Facebook Alternative, Set To Launch|date=February 1, 2013|accessdate=February 2, 2013|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|first=Nick|last=Wing}}</ref><ref name="Harper">{{cite news | url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:WSTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=14430E528079E320&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0FB3382EE6AD1E46 | title=Inside the Beltway | date=February 1, 2013 | agency=Washington Times | accessdate=February 1, 2013 | author=Harper, Jennifer | location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref>
